A digital creator introduced his series of images featuring babies skydiving on Facebook.

column4: Winner of Sony World Photography Award in 2023
column5: This AI generated image was submitted for a major photography competition and won the top prize.
Mumbai-based artist Ashish Jose has employed AI to generate hyper-realistic images of elderly women skating on the street.

column4: Featured in New York Post article
column5: Part of a viral series of images rendered by AI. This one depicts the late Queen Elizabeth II breaking it down on the dance floor.
Part of a trend of making images featuring huge fruits and vegetables. People even travelled to try and see these fruits.

column4: Featured in Kellogg Insight article about AI
column5: Example of realistic photo that stands out as fake because of distorted fingers and missing watch features.
This image of the Pope in a designer jacket was first published on Reddit and went viral because of how real it looks.

This was part of a series of AI content showing Will Smith eating spaghetti over a number of years. The images got more and more realistic as the AI software improved. Will Smith himself even parodied the videos.
This meme was popularized in July 2023 after the launch of Meta's new text-based app Threads.
Images like these of the former Brazilian president were spread to attack him by his political opponents.
Part of a series of AI images depicting celebrities playing their own video games.
A developer on X went viral after sharing what appeared to be vintage-style snaps at a house party.
This image of Katy Perry at the Met Gala went viral. Even Katy Perry’s mother thought it was real. But she wasn’t even at the event.
This image was from the first viral AI commercial. A great example of how far AI has evolved since its early days.
This image went viral during Hurricane Milton. It was used by right wing MAGA supporters to show the effects of Biden’s lack of support for residents in the wake of the hurricane.
The spread of misinformation about the Middle East conflict on social media makes it even harder for people to stay accurately informed — and AI-generated images like this only add to the confusion.
Multiple verified X accounts shared images like this showing an explosion near the Pentagon. People believed it and the stock market even dipped as a result.
The curious image, which has the overall tone and feel of a film photo taken in the late 1980s, was shared on X, where it racked up over 22 million views in just two days.
This featured as part of a viral series of pop culture characters in strange situations.
Part of a trend that showed the world’s richest people as if they were living in developing countries

In early 2024, a wave of images hit Facebook that centered on an odd theme: plastic bottles. These images commonly featured an AI-generated photo of an object constructed entirely of plastic bottles, alongside the person responsible for its creation.
An image of Julian Assange looking sick in Belmarsh prison went viral at the end of 2023.
The image went viral to show support to Israel. But quickly people start calling it out
Part of a growing trend of fabricated images and videos of historical events — blurring the line between fact and fiction.
Trump posted these images on his Truth account as part of his campaign, not realizing the creator of these AI generated images were created for satire.
A set of images went viral, claiming to be from the recent floods reportedly caused by relentless monsoon rains and overflowing rivers in Bangladesh.

column4: Shared via Medium, Washington Post, and more
column5: This image and others like it were widely shared in response to attacks on Ukraine by Russia.
This image went viral because of how realistic it looked, sparking online debate about guns in public spaces.
Late last year this video went viral. It was a video showing people rescuing a young polar bear that was stranded on a melting iceberg.
Images like this have been shared widely on social media, adding to the ongoing debate about the war in Gaza.
After the Olympics these images went viral, showing the filthy streets caused by the crowds.
When riots were happening in France, images like these depicting the French leader, went viral on social media.

A photographer used AI to create a series of AI images that showed events in Cuba as modern day photos. This image depicts the perilous 90-mile journey from Havana to Florida that some Cubans attempt.
During the LA fire videos like this went viral, convincing people that the fires had spread to the city.
These images went viral, showing houses on the shore being swamped by waves in the wake of the hurricane.
Images like these, depicting Pikachu at a Turkish protest, recently went viral across social media.
These images depicting an earthquake that never actually occurred in 2001 went viral.
A viral video claiming to show a whale swallowing a yacht went viral but it’s just an AI-generated hoax

This clip shows the formation of a huge tornado over the city. Upon closer inspection, we noticed inconsistencies in the videos, such as reversed vehicle movements, misshaped homes and vehicles, and joined windows, suggesting that these videos are likely AI-generated.
A fake video of a UFO crash site in Arizona went viral but it’s just an AI-generated hoax from a TikToker
